    "Risk Parity (All Weather, unlevered)": {
      "rule": "Bridgewater All Weather (Dalio, 1996): a 60/40 book holds 60% of its dollars in equities but ~90% of its RISK there, so it is not actually diversified. Weight inversely to volatility instead, equalising each asset's risk contribution. The mechanism is leverage aversion (Asness, Frazzini & Pedersen 2012, FAJ, 'Leverage Aversion and Risk Parity'): investors who cannot borrow bid up high-beta assets, leaving low-beta assets better risk-adjusted returns; supporting evidence in Chaves et al. (2011) and Clarke et al. (2013). This is the UNLEVERED variant because the project forbids leverage, so judge it on Sharpe and drawdown, not total return. One conventional parameter (60-day vol).",
